[2026-03-17T15:36:12Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01H7bQSmgJ4Z98hYNnuCgWwb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Self-Evolution System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche's self-evolution system analyzes workflow run history and user feedback to\n     6→automatically improve prompts, add validation steps, and refine workflows over\n     7→time. It is a daemon-side post-run pipeline that triggers after every workflow\n     8→completion, applies changes directly to project files, and maintains a structured\n     9→audit trail.\n    10→\n    11→The system draws on the ACE (Agentic Context Engineering) framework for prompt\n    12→evolution — treating prompts as structured, itemized playbooks that accumulate\n    13→lessons rather than monolithic documents that get rewritten.\n    14→\n    15→**Scope (this version):** Additive changes only. Prompt updates, new script\n    16→steps, new agent steps, new wiring. No step removal or mutation of existing step\n    17→definitions.\n    18→\n    19→## Architecture\n    20→\n    21→The evolution system is a multi-stage pipeline with three specialized output\n    22→branches. The LLM handles classification, reflection, and content generation.\n    23→Deterministic Go code handles structural manipulation (DSL editing, file I/O,\n    24→audit logging).\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n    28→                    │         Workflow Run Completes       │\n    29→                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n    30→                                   │\n    31→                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n    32→                    │           Collector                  │\n    33→                    │  Gathers: run results, history.log,  │\n    34→                    │  step outputs, knowledge base,       │\n    35→                    │  current prompts + workflow          │\n    36→                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n    37→                                   │\n    38→                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n    39→                    │         Classifier (LLM)            │\n    40→                    │  Categorizes run prompt:             │\n    41→                    │  bug | feedback | feature |          │\n    42→                    │  enhancement | chore                 │\n    43→                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n    44→                                   │\n    45→                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n    46→                    │         Reflector (LLM)              │\n    47→                    │  ACE-style: examines traces,         │\n    48→                    │  extracts structured lessons          │\n    49→                    │  (bullets with metadata)              │\n    50→                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n    51→                                   │\n    52→              ┌────────────────────┼────────────────────┐\n    53→              │                    │                     │\n    54→   ┌──────────▼────────┐ ┌────────▼──────────┐ ┌───────▼──────────┐\n    55→   │  Prompt Curator    │ │  Script Generator │ │  DSL Mutator     │\n    56→   │  (LLM + dedup)     │ │  (LLM)            │ │  (Go code)       │\n    57→   │                    │ │                    │ │                   │\n    58→   │  Merges lessons    │ │  Writes new        │ │  Adds steps,     │\n    59→   │  into prompt files │ │  checker/linter    │ │  wiring, collects │\n    60→   │  as structured     │ │  scripts           │ │  to .cloche file  │\n    61→   │  bullets           │ │                    │ │                   │\n    62→   └────────┬───────────┘ └────────┬───────────┘ └───────┬──────────┘\n    63→            │                      │                      │\n    64→            └──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┘\n    65→                                   │\n    66→                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n    67→                    │         Audit Logger                 │\n    68→                    │  Records all changes + reasons        │\n    69→                    │  Updates knowledge base summary       │\n    70→                    │  Snapshots pre-change state           │\n    71→                    └─────────────────────────────────────┘\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→The three branches fire independently based on lesson category. A single\n    75→evolution pass may produce changes across multiple branches, or none at all.\n    76→\n    77→## Multi-Project Scoping\n    78→\n    79→The daemon supports multiple concurrent cloche instances across different\n    80→projects (and multiple runs within the same project). Every run record includes\n    81→`project_dir` — the absolute path to the project directory where `cloche run`\n    82→was invoked.\n    83→\n    84→All evolution state is scoped by project_dir + workflow_name:\n    85→- SQLite queries filter by project_dir\n    86→- Knowledge bases live at `<project_dir>/.cloche/evolution/knowledge/<workflow>.md`\n    87→- Evolution passes for different projects/workflows run independently\n    88→- One evolution pass at a time per project+workflow (mutex)\n    89→\n    90→## Data Collection\n    91→\n    92→### New Signals Captured Per Run\n    93→\n    94→| Signal               | Where captured                        | Notes                          |\n    95→|----------------------|---------------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n    96→| Assembled prompt     | Prompt adapter, before LLM invocation | Full text sent to the agent    |\n    97→| Agent stdout         | Prompt adapter, after agent returns   | Full LLM response              |\n    98→| Run prompt class     | Classifier LLM, post-run             | bug/feedback/feature/etc.      |\n    99→| Retry count per step | Prompt adapter attempt tracking       | Already in filesystem, add to SQLite |\n   100→| Project directory    | CLI sends to daemon via gRPC          | Currently implicit             |\n   101→\n   102→### Run Prompt Classification\n   103→\n   104→The Classifier examines each run's `--prompt` text and categorizes it:\n   105→\n   106→- **bug** — fixing something broken; indicates a gap the system should reflect on\n   107→  for patterns in its approach to software development\n   108→- **feedback** — code review style issues (DRY, SOLID, architecture); things\n   109→  caught in a typical review cycle that the system should watch its output for\n   110→- **feature** — new functionality; normal work\n   111→- **enhancement** — improving existing functionality\n   112→- **chore** — maintenance; no evolution signal\n   113→\n   114→Bug and feedback runs are the primary evolution drivers. Features and\n   115→enhancements provide background context but don't typically trigger changes.\n   116→Classification happens via LLM inference on the prompt text — no explicit\n   117→`--type` flag needed from the user.\n   118→\n   119→### SQLite Schema Additions\n   120→\n   121→```sql\n   122→-- Add project scoping to runs\n   123→ALTER TABLE runs ADD COLUMN project_dir TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '';\n   124→\n   125→-- Extend step_executions with captured data\n   126→ALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN prompt_text TEXT;\n   127→ALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN agent_output TEXT;\n   128→ALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN attempt_number INTEGER DEFAULT 1;\n   129→\n   130→-- Track evolution passes\n   131→CREATE TABLE evolution_log (\n   132→    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n   133→    project_dir TEXT NOT NULL,\n   134→    workflow_name TEXT NOT NULL,\n   135→    trigger_run_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n   136→    created_at DATETIME NOT NULL,\n   137→    classification TEXT,\n   138→    changes_json TEXT NOT NULL,\n   139→    knowledge_delta TEXT\n   140→);\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→### On-Disk Evolution State\n   144→\n   145→```\n   146→.cloche/\n   147→  evolution/\n   148→    log.jsonl                   # append-only audit trail (one JSON object per line)\n   149→    knowledge/\n   150→      develop.md                # ACE-style knowledge base for 'develop' workflow\n   151→    snapshots/\n   152→      <timestamp>-<filename>    # pre-change backups for revert\n   153→    fitness/\n   154→      develop.jsonl             # JSONL fitness records per workflow (GEPA)\n   155→    population/\n   156→      <step-name>/\n   157→        candidate-NNN.md        # candidate prompt variant\n   158→        meta.jsonl              # candidate metadata (id, status, parent, score)\n   159→        assignments.jsonl       # run→candidate mapping\n   160→```\n   161→\n   162→## Pipeline Stages\n   163→\n   164→### Stage 1: Collector\n   165→\n   166→Triggers after every run completion. Gathers:\n   167→\n   168→1. All runs for this project+workflow since the last evolution pass (tracked via\n   169→   `evolution_log.trigger_run_id`)\n   170→2. The accumulated knowledge base (`knowledge/<workflow>.md`)\n   171→3. Current prompt files referenced by the workflow\n   172→4. The current `.cloche` workflow DSL file\n   173→5. Runs classified as \"bug\" or \"feedback\" carry more weight in analysis\n   174→\n   175→If there are no new runs since the last evolution, the pipeline short-circuits.\n   176→\n   177→### Stage 2: Classifier (LLM)\n   178→\n   179→For each unclassified run, the Classifier examines the run prompt and assigns a\n   180→category. The classification is stored in the run record (SQLite) for use by the\n   181→Reflector and for future queries.\n   182→\n   183→### Stage 3: Reflector (LLM)\n   184→\n   185→The Reflector examines execution traces and extracts structured lessons. It\n   186→receives the collected run data (step results, failure logs, retry counts), the\n   187→current knowledge base, and the current prompts and workflow.\n   188→\n   189→It produces delta entries — structured lessons:\n   190→\n   191→```json\n   192→{\n   193→  \"lessons\": [\n   194→    {\n   195→      \"id\": \"lesson-20260224-001\",\n   196→      \"category\": \"prompt_improvement\",\n   197→      \"target\": \"prompts/implement.md\",\n   198→      \"insight\": \"Agent consistently produces unsanitized HTML output in form handlers. 4 of last 6 bug-type runs involved XSS.\",\n   199→      \"suggested_action\": \"Add explicit rule: always sanitize user inputs with html.EscapeString() before template rendering\",\n   200→      \"evidence\": [\"run-abc\", \"run-def\", \"run-ghi\", \"run-jkl\"],\n   201→      \"confidence\": \"high\"\n   202→    },\n   203→    {\n   204→      \"id\": \"lesson-20260224-002\",\n   205→      \"category\": \"new_step\",\n   206→      \"step_type\": \"script\",\n   207→      \"insight\": \"No static security analysis in workflow. Security bugs only caught by user reports post-deployment.\",\n   208→      \"suggested_action\": \"Add gosec script step after test, wire failures to fix\",\n   209→      \"evidence\": [\"run-abc\", \"run-def\"],\n   210→      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n   211→    }\n   212→  ]\n   213→}\n   214→```\n   215→\n   216→Confidence levels (high/medium/low) are based on evidence count and pattern\n   217→consistency. Only lessons meeting the configured minimum confidence proceed to\n   218→the executor branches.\n   219→\n   220→**Knowledge base deduplication:** After confidence filtering, the Reflector\n   221→cross-references generated lesson IDs against the current knowledge base text.\n   222→Lessons whose ID already appears in the knowledge base are dropped, preventing\n   223→the same lessons from being re-surfaced across evolution cycles. The\n   224→Orchestrator applies a second-layer ID filter as a guard, ensuring that even if\n   225→the Reflector misses a duplicate, previously applied lessons are not\n   226→re-processed.\n   227→\n   228→### Stage 4: Executor Branches\n   229→\n   230→Based on each lesson's `category`, it routes to one of three branches.\n   231→\n   232→#### Branch A: Prompt Curator (LLM + deterministic dedup)\n   233→\n   234→Handles `prompt_improvement` lessons.\n   235→\n   236→- Receives the current prompt file content and the lesson\n   237→- **Content-change guard:** Before calling the LLM, the curator checks whether\n   238→  the lesson's key insight or suggested action is already present in the current\n   239→  prompt text (case-insensitive substring match). If the lesson is already\n   240→  incorporated, the curator returns immediately without calling the LLM and\n   241→  without rewriting the file. This prevents churn, snapshot bloat, and\n   242→  regression risk from unnecessary rewrites.\n   243→- ACE-style curation: merges the lesson into the prompt as a structured\n   244→  bullet/rule\n   245→- Deduplication: checks for semantic overlap with existing bullets; if a lesson\n   246→  refines an existing bullet, it updates in place rather than appending\n   247→- Code-fence stripping: LLM responses are cleaned of markdown code fences\n   248→  (` ``` `) before writing, extracting only the content between fences. This\n   249→  prevents meta-commentary or formatting artifacts from leaking into prompt files.\n   250→- Conversational response validation: after stripping code fences, the output is\n   251→  checked for conversational markers (e.g. \"I need write permission\", \"Here is\n   252→  the updated prompt:\", \"Could you grant access\"). If the LLM returned\n   253→  meta-conversation text instead of prompt content, the curator falls back to\n   254→  appending the lesson directly as a structured bullet rather than trusting the\n   255→  LLM output. This prevents prompt file corruption when the LLM produces\n   256→  interactive-style responses.\n   257→- **Post-write sanity check:** After writing the updated prompt to disk, the\n   258→  curator re-reads the file and validates it: the content must be non-empty,\n   259→  must not start with conversational phrases, and must contain at least one\n   260→  markdown heading (`#`). If the sanity check fails, the curator restores the\n   261→  file from the pre-change snapshot and returns a `prompt_update_rollback`\n   262→  change entry instead of `prompt_update`. The snapshot is preserved as\n   263→  evidence.\n   264→- Output: the modified prompt file content, written to disk\n   265→\n   266→#### Branch B: Script Generator (LLM)\n   267→\n   268→Handles `new_step` lessons where step_type is \"script\" or \"agent\".\n   269→\n   270→- Receives the lesson describing what check or analysis is needed\n   271→- Generates a script file (shell, Python, etc.) implementing the check, or a\n   272→  prompt file for agent steps\n   273→- Script/prompt is written to the project directory (e.g.,\n   274→  `scripts/security-scan.sh` or `prompts/review.md`)\n   275→- Output: the file path and content\n   276→\n   277→#### Branch C: DSL Mutator (deterministic Go code)\n   278→\n   279→Handles structural workflow changes. Receives structured proposals and applies\n   280→them to the `.cloche` workflow file. Four operations:\n   281→\n   282→**Add Step Definition:**\n   283→```json\n   284→{\n   285→  \"op\": \"add_step\",\n   286→  \"name\": \"security-scan\",\n   287→  \"type\": \"script\",\n   288→  \"config\": {\n   289→    \"run\": \"gosec ./...\",\n   290→    \"results\": [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n   291→  }\n   292→}\n   293→```\n   294→\n   295→Parses the workflow file, inserts the step definition, serializes back.\n   296→\n   297→**Add Wiring:**\n   298→```json\n   299→{\n   300→  \"op\": \"add_wire\",\n   301→  \"wires\": [\n   302→    {\"from\": \"test\", \"result\": \"success\", \"to\": \"security-scan\"},\n   303→    {\"from\": \"security-scan\", \"result\": \"fail\", \"to\": \"fix\"}\n   304→  ]\n   305→}\n   306→```\n   307→\n   308→Appends wires to the wiring section.\n   309→\n   310→**Rewire Result:**\n   311→```json\n   312→{\n   313→  \"op\": \"rewire_result\",\n   314→  \"from\": \"test\",\n   315→  \"result\": \"success\",\n   316→  \"old_to\": \"done\",\n   317→  \"new_to\": \"security-scan\"\n   318→}\n   319→```\n   320→\n   321→Changes the target of an existing wire. Used by the orchestrator when inserting\n   322→a new step into the graph: it finds a wire pointing to `done`, rewires it to\n   323→the new step, then wires the new step's results to terminals. This splices the\n   324→new step into the existing flow rather than creating a disconnected node.\n   325→\n   326→**Update Collect:**\n   327→```json\n   328→{\n   329→  \"op\": \"update_collect\",\n   330→  \"collect_target\": \"done\",\n   331→  \"add_conditions\": [\n   332→    {\"step\": \"security-scan\", \"result\": \"success\"}\n   333→  ]\n   334→}\n   335→```\n   336→\n   337→Finds the matching `collect` clause and adds the new condition.\n   338→\n   339→**Validation gate:** After any mutation, the mutator calls\n   340→`domain.Workflow.Validate()` on the result. If validation fails, the mutation is\n   341→rejected, the original file is preserved, and the failure is logged.\n   342→\n   343→**DSL Serializer:** The mutator requires a round-trip-preserving serializer —\n   344→parse into an AST that retains comments and whitespace, modify the AST, serialize\n   345→back. This preserves user formatting and comments.\n   346→\n   347→Branches B and C often fire together — a new script step needs both the script\n   348→file (B) and the DSL wiring (C).\n   349→\n   350→### Stage 5: Audit Logger\n   351→\n   352→After all changes are applied:\n   353→\n   354→1. **Snapshot** — copies pre-change versions of all modified files to\n   355→   `.cloche/evolution/snapshots/`\n   356→2. **Restore** — restores a file from a named snapshot (used by the Curator\n   357→   to roll back corrupted writes)\n   358→3. **Log** — appends a JSONL entry to `.cloche/evolution/log.jsonl` and inserts\n   359→   into the `evolution_log` SQLite table\n   360→4. **Knowledge base update** — merges the Reflector's lessons into\n   361→   `knowledge/<workflow>.jsonl` with ID-based deduplication and optional\n   362→   pruning via `MaxPromptBullets`\n   363→\n   364→## Knowledge Base Structure\n   365→\n   366→The knowledge base is a JSONL file — one JSON object per line, each\n   367→representing a `Lesson`. Lessons are keyed by `id` for deduplication: if a\n   368→lesson with the same ID already exists, it is updated in place rather than\n   369→appended. When `MaxPromptBullets` is configured and the total number of\n   370→lessons exceeds that limit, the oldest entries are pruned to stay within\n   371→bounds.\n   372→\n   373→```jsonl\n   374→{\"id\":\"P001\",\"category\":\"prompt_improvement\",\"insight\":\"Always sanitize user inputs with html.EscapeString() before template rendering\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add sanitization rule to prompt\",\"evidence\":[\"run-abc\",\"run-def\"],\"confidence\":\"high\"}\n   375→{\"id\":\"W001\",\"category\":\"new_step\",\"step_type\":\"script\",\"insight\":\"Added gosec security scan step\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add gosec step to workflow\",\"evidence\":[\"run-abc\",\"run-def\"],\"confidence\":\"high\"}\n   376→{\"id\":\"F001\",\"category\":\"prompt_improvement\",\"insight\":\"Test timeout failures correlate with database connection setup\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add retry guidance to prompt\",\"evidence\":[\"run-ghi\",\"run-jkl\"],\"confidence\":\"medium\"}\n   377→```\n   378→\n   379→The structured JSONL format enables reliable deduplication by lesson ID and\n   380→programmatic querying. Lessons that are superseded by newer insights with the\n   381→same ID are replaced automatically.\n   382→\n   383→## Trigger Logic\n   384→\n   385→### When Evolution Runs\n   386→\n   387→The pipeline triggers in the daemon after every workflow run completes (success\n   388→or failure). Smart throttling prevents waste:\n   389→\n   390→- **Debounce:** If runs complete in rapid succession (parallel runs on the same\n   391→  project), wait a configurable period (default 30s) after the last completion\n   392→  before triggering. This batches multiple runs into one analysis pass.\n   393→- **Mutex:** If an evolution pass is already in progress for this\n   394→  project+workflow, skip. The next run completion will pick up the slack.\n   395→- **No-op detection:** If the Reflector finds nothing actionable (clean feature\n   396→  runs, no patterns), the pipeline logs \"no changes\" and exits without firing\n   397→  the executor branches.\n   398→\n   399→### History Window\n   400→\n   401→The Collector gathers all runs since the last evolution pass (tracked via\n   402→`evolution_log.trigger_run_id`). The knowledge base provides the long-term\n   403→memory — once raw runs are analyzed, their lessons persist in the knowledge base\n   404→even as the raw data ages out. This gives the system both recency (raw run data)\n   405→and continuity (accumulated knowledge).\n   406→\n   407→## Protocol Changes\n   408→\n   409→### gRPC (CLI to Daemon)\n   410→\n   411→```protobuf\n   412→message RunRequest {\n   413→  string workflow = 1;\n   414→  string prompt = 2;\n   415→  string project_dir = 3;   // NEW\n   416→}\n   417→```\n   418→\n   419→### Status Protocol (Agent to Daemon)\n   420→\n   421→```protobuf\n   422→message StepStarted {\n   423→  string step_name = 1;\n   424→  string prompt_text = 2;    // NEW: assembled prompt\n   425→}\n   426→\n   427→message StepCompleted {\n   428→  string step_name = 1;\n   429→  string result = 2;\n   430→  string agent_output = 3;   // NEW: LLM response\n   431→  int32 attempt_number = 4;  // NEW\n   432→}\n   433→```\n   434→\n   435→### Prompt Adapter Changes\n   436→\n   437→The prompt adapter captures the assembled prompt text before invoking the agent\n   438→and the agent's stdout after it returns. Both are forwarded to the daemon via\n   439→the status protocol. No changes to prompt assembly logic — the evolution system\n   440→modifies prompt files on disk, and the existing `file()` mechanism picks up\n   441→changes on the next run.\n   442→\n   443→## Configuration\n   444→\n   445→Per-project in `.cloche/config`:\n   446→\n   447→```toml\n   448→[evolution]\n   449→enabled = true                # master switch\n   450→debounce_seconds = 30         # wait after last run before analyzing\n   451→min_confidence = \"medium\"     # minimum lesson confidence to act on\n   452→max_prompt_bullets = 50       # cap on knowledge bullets per prompt\n   453→```\n   454→\n   455→Evolution is enabled by default. Users can disable it per-project for static\n   456→workflows.\n   457→\n   458→## GEPA: Fitness Evaluation and Pareto Front\n   459→\n   460→The Guided Evolutionary Prompt Adaptation (GEPA) subsystem extends the evolution\n   461→pipeline with multi-objective fitness evaluation for population-based prompt\n   462→evolution. It lives in `internal/evolution/fitness.go`.\n   463→\n   464→### Fitness Records\n   465→\n   466→Each completed run is evaluated into a `FitnessRecord` containing:\n   467→- **RunID / WorkflowName / Candidate** — identifies the run and its candidate\n   468→  (e.g. a prompt version)\n   469→- **Success** — whether the run reached `succeeded` state\n   470→- **RetryCount** — number of step re-executions (detected by counting duplicate\n   471→  step names in execution history)\n   472→- **Duration** — wall-clock time from start to completion\n   473→\n   474→Records are persisted as JSONL at `.cloche/evolution/fitness/<workflow>.jsonl`.\n   475→\n   476→### Aggregation\n   477→\n   478→`AggregateFitness` groups records by candidate and computes two objectives:\n   479→\n   480→1. **Success rate** — fraction of runs that succeeded\n   481→2. **Efficiency** — `1 / (1 + avgRetries + avgDurationMinutes)`, rewarding\n   482→   faster candidates with fewer retries\n   483→\n   484→### Pareto Front\n   485→\n   486→`ComputeParetoFront` returns the non-dominated set using standard Pareto\n   487→dominance: candidate A dominates B when A is at least as good in all objectives\n   488→and strictly better in at least one. The front represents the optimal tradeoff\n   489→between reliability and speed — no candidate on the front can be improved in one\n   490→objective without sacrificing the other.\n   491→\n   492→### Population Configuration\n   493→\n   494→Population-based evolution is controlled by `PopulationConfig`:\n   495→\n   496→```go\n   497→type PopulationConfig struct {\n   498→    Enabled          bool\n   499→    MaxCandidates    int\n   500→    MinRunsToPromote int\n   501→}\n   502→```\n   503→\n   504→## Future Work (Out of Scope)\n   505→\n   506→- **Step removal/mutation** — modifying or removing existing step definitions\n   507→  (higher risk, needs careful design around backwards compatibility)\n   508→- **`cloche evolve --revert <evo-id>`** — automated revert from snapshots\n   509→- **Helpfulness tracking** — automatically detecting whether applied lessons\n   510→  actually reduced failure rates, and pruning unhelpful ones\n   511→- **Cross-project learning** — sharing knowledge base insights across projects\n   512→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"70e783a4-e8f4-4ca0-9162-12684b626521","uuid":"494ab460-85b6-4770-8963-791affc31815","timestamp":"2026-03-17T15:35:32.046Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-24-self-evolution-design.md","content":"# Self-Evolution System Design\n\n## Overview\n\nCloche's self-evolution system analyzes workflow run history and user feedback to\nautomatically improve prompts, add validation steps, and refine workflows over\ntime. It is a daemon-side post-run pipeline that triggers after every workflow\ncompletion, applies changes directly to project files, and maintains a structured\naudit trail.\n\nThe system draws on the ACE (Agentic Context Engineering) framework for prompt\nevolution — treating prompts as structured, itemized playbooks that accumulate\nlessons rather than monolithic documents that get rewritten.\n\n**Scope (this version):** Additive changes only. Prompt updates, new script\nsteps, new agent steps, new wiring. No step removal or mutation of existing step\ndefinitions.\n\n## Architecture\n\nThe evolution system is a multi-stage pipeline with three specialized output\nbranches. The LLM handles classification, reflection, and content generation.\nDeterministic Go code handles structural manipulation (DSL editing, file I/O,\naudit logging).\n\n```\n                    ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n                    │         Workflow Run Completes       │\n                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n                                   │\n                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n                    │           Collector                  │\n                    │  Gathers: run results, history.log,  │\n                    │  step outputs, knowledge base,       │\n                    │  current prompts + workflow          │\n                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n                                   │\n                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n                    │         Classifier (LLM)            │\n                    │  Categorizes run prompt:             │\n                    │  bug | feedback | feature |          │\n                    │  enhancement | chore                 │\n                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n                                   │\n                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n                    │         Reflector (LLM)              │\n                    │  ACE-style: examines traces,         │\n                    │  extracts structured lessons          │\n                    │  (bullets with metadata)              │\n                    └──────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n                                   │\n              ┌────────────────────┼────────────────────┐\n              │                    │                     │\n   ┌──────────▼────────┐ ┌────────▼──────────┐ ┌───────▼──────────┐\n   │  Prompt Curator    │ │  Script Generator │ │  DSL Mutator     │\n   │  (LLM + dedup)     │ │  (LLM)            │ │  (Go code)       │\n   │                    │ │                    │ │                   │\n   │  Merges lessons    │ │  Writes new        │ │  Adds steps,     │\n   │  into prompt files │ │  checker/linter    │ │  wiring, collects │\n   │  as structured     │ │  scripts           │ │  to .cloche file  │\n   │  bullets           │ │                    │ │                   │\n   └────────┬───────────┘ └────────┬───────────┘ └───────┬──────────┘\n            │                      │                      │\n            └──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┘\n                                   │\n                    ┌──────────────▼──────────────────────┐\n                    │         Audit Logger                 │\n                    │  Records all changes + reasons        │\n                    │  Updates knowledge base summary       │\n                    │  Snapshots pre-change state           │\n                    └─────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\nThe three branches fire independently based on lesson category. A single\nevolution pass may produce changes across multiple branches, or none at all.\n\n## Multi-Project Scoping\n\nThe daemon supports multiple concurrent cloche instances across different\nprojects (and multiple runs within the same project). Every run record includes\n`project_dir` — the absolute path to the project directory where `cloche run`\nwas invoked.\n\nAll evolution state is scoped by project_dir + workflow_name:\n- SQLite queries filter by project_dir\n- Knowledge bases live at `<project_dir>/.cloche/evolution/knowledge/<workflow>.md`\n- Evolution passes for different projects/workflows run independently\n- One evolution pass at a time per project+workflow (mutex)\n\n## Data Collection\n\n### New Signals Captured Per Run\n\n| Signal               | Where captured                        | Notes                          |\n|----------------------|---------------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n| Assembled prompt     | Prompt adapter, before LLM invocation | Full text sent to the agent    |\n| Agent stdout         | Prompt adapter, after agent returns   | Full LLM response              |\n| Run prompt class     | Classifier LLM, post-run             | bug/feedback/feature/etc.      |\n| Retry count per step | Prompt adapter attempt tracking       | Already in filesystem, add to SQLite |\n| Project directory    | CLI sends to daemon via gRPC          | Currently implicit             |\n\n### Run Prompt Classification\n\nThe Classifier examines each run's `--prompt` text and categorizes it:\n\n- **bug** — fixing something broken; indicates a gap the system should reflect on\n  for patterns in its approach to software development\n- **feedback** — code review style issues (DRY, SOLID, architecture); things\n  caught in a typical review cycle that the system should watch its output for\n- **feature** — new functionality; normal work\n- **enhancement** — improving existing functionality\n- **chore** — maintenance; no evolution signal\n\nBug and feedback runs are the primary evolution drivers. Features and\nenhancements provide background context but don't typically trigger changes.\nClassification happens via LLM inference on the prompt text — no explicit\n`--type` flag needed from the user.\n\n### SQLite Schema Additions\n\n```sql\n-- Add project scoping to runs\nALTER TABLE runs ADD COLUMN project_dir TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '';\n\n-- Extend step_executions with captured data\nALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN prompt_text TEXT;\nALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN agent_output TEXT;\nALTER TABLE step_executions ADD COLUMN attempt_number INTEGER DEFAULT 1;\n\n-- Track evolution passes\nCREATE TABLE evolution_log (\n    id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n    project_dir TEXT NOT NULL,\n    workflow_name TEXT NOT NULL,\n    trigger_run_id TEXT NOT NULL,\n    created_at DATETIME NOT NULL,\n    classification TEXT,\n    changes_json TEXT NOT NULL,\n    knowledge_delta TEXT\n);\n```\n\n### On-Disk Evolution State\n\n```\n.cloche/\n  evolution/\n    log.jsonl                   # append-only audit trail (one JSON object per line)\n    knowledge/\n      develop.md                # ACE-style knowledge base for 'develop' workflow\n    snapshots/\n      <timestamp>-<filename>    # pre-change backups for revert\n    fitness/\n      develop.jsonl             # JSONL fitness records per workflow (GEPA)\n    population/\n      <step-name>/\n        candidate-NNN.md        # candidate prompt variant\n        meta.jsonl              # candidate metadata (id, status, parent, score)\n        assignments.jsonl       # run→candidate mapping\n```\n\n## Pipeline Stages\n\n### Stage 1: Collector\n\nTriggers after every run completion. Gathers:\n\n1. All runs for this project+workflow since the last evolution pass (tracked via\n   `evolution_log.trigger_run_id`)\n2. The accumulated knowledge base (`knowledge/<workflow>.md`)\n3. Current prompt files referenced by the workflow\n4. The current `.cloche` workflow DSL file\n5. Runs classified as \"bug\" or \"feedback\" carry more weight in analysis\n\nIf there are no new runs since the last evolution, the pipeline short-circuits.\n\n### Stage 2: Classifier (LLM)\n\nFor each unclassified run, the Classifier examines the run prompt and assigns a\ncategory. The classification is stored in the run record (SQLite) for use by the\nReflector and for future queries.\n\n### Stage 3: Reflector (LLM)\n\nThe Reflector examines execution traces and extracts structured lessons. It\nreceives the collected run data (step results, failure logs, retry counts), the\ncurrent knowledge base, and the current prompts and workflow.\n\nIt produces delta entries — structured lessons:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"lessons\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"lesson-20260224-001\",\n      \"category\": \"prompt_improvement\",\n      \"target\": \"prompts/implement.md\",\n      \"insight\": \"Agent consistently produces unsanitized HTML output in form handlers. 4 of last 6 bug-type runs involved XSS.\",\n      \"suggested_action\": \"Add explicit rule: always sanitize user inputs with html.EscapeString() before template rendering\",\n      \"evidence\": [\"run-abc\", \"run-def\", \"run-ghi\", \"run-jkl\"],\n      \"confidence\": \"high\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"lesson-20260224-002\",\n      \"category\": \"new_step\",\n      \"step_type\": \"script\",\n      \"insight\": \"No static security analysis in workflow. Security bugs only caught by user reports post-deployment.\",\n      \"suggested_action\": \"Add gosec script step after test, wire failures to fix\",\n      \"evidence\": [\"run-abc\", \"run-def\"],\n      \"confidence\": \"medium\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nConfidence levels (high/medium/low) are based on evidence count and pattern\nconsistency. Only lessons meeting the configured minimum confidence proceed to\nthe executor branches.\n\n**Knowledge base deduplication:** After confidence filtering, the Reflector\ncross-references generated lesson IDs against the current knowledge base text.\nLessons whose ID already appears in the knowledge base are dropped, preventing\nthe same lessons from being re-surfaced across evolution cycles. The\nOrchestrator applies a second-layer ID filter as a guard, ensuring that even if\nthe Reflector misses a duplicate, previously applied lessons are not\nre-processed.\n\n### Stage 4: Executor Branches\n\nBased on each lesson's `category`, it routes to one of three branches.\n\n#### Branch A: Prompt Curator (LLM + deterministic dedup)\n\nHandles `prompt_improvement` lessons.\n\n- Receives the current prompt file content and the lesson\n- **Content-change guard:** Before calling the LLM, the curator checks whether\n  the lesson's key insight or suggested action is already present in the current\n  prompt text (case-insensitive substring match). If the lesson is already\n  incorporated, the curator returns immediately without calling the LLM and\n  without rewriting the file. This prevents churn, snapshot bloat, and\n  regression risk from unnecessary rewrites.\n- ACE-style curation: merges the lesson into the prompt as a structured\n  bullet/rule\n- Deduplication: checks for semantic overlap with existing bullets; if a lesson\n  refines an existing bullet, it updates in place rather than appending\n- Code-fence stripping: LLM responses are cleaned of markdown code fences\n  (` ``` `) before writing, extracting only the content between fences. This\n  prevents meta-commentary or formatting artifacts from leaking into prompt files.\n- Conversational response validation: after stripping code fences, the output is\n  checked for conversational markers (e.g. \"I need write permission\", \"Here is\n  the updated prompt:\", \"Could you grant access\"). If the LLM returned\n  meta-conversation text instead of prompt content, the curator falls back to\n  appending the lesson directly as a structured bullet rather than trusting the\n  LLM output. This prevents prompt file corruption when the LLM produces\n  interactive-style responses.\n- **Post-write sanity check:** After writing the updated prompt to disk, the\n  curator re-reads the file and validates it: the content must be non-empty,\n  must not start with conversational phrases, and must contain at least one\n  markdown heading (`#`). If the sanity check fails, the curator restores the\n  file from the pre-change snapshot and returns a `prompt_update_rollback`\n  change entry instead of `prompt_update`. The snapshot is preserved as\n  evidence.\n- Output: the modified prompt file content, written to disk\n\n#### Branch B: Script Generator (LLM)\n\nHandles `new_step` lessons where step_type is \"script\" or \"agent\".\n\n- Receives the lesson describing what check or analysis is needed\n- Generates a script file (shell, Python, etc.) implementing the check, or a\n  prompt file for agent steps\n- Script/prompt is written to the project directory (e.g.,\n  `scripts/security-scan.sh` or `prompts/review.md`)\n- Output: the file path and content\n\n#### Branch C: DSL Mutator (deterministic Go code)\n\nHandles structural workflow changes. Receives structured proposals and applies\nthem to the `.cloche` workflow file. Four operations:\n\n**Add Step Definition:**\n```json\n{\n  \"op\": \"add_step\",\n  \"name\": \"security-scan\",\n  \"type\": \"script\",\n  \"config\": {\n    \"run\": \"gosec ./...\",\n    \"results\": [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nParses the workflow file, inserts the step definition, serializes back.\n\n**Add Wiring:**\n```json\n{\n  \"op\": \"add_wire\",\n  \"wires\": [\n    {\"from\": \"test\", \"result\": \"success\", \"to\": \"security-scan\"},\n    {\"from\": \"security-scan\", \"result\": \"fail\", \"to\": \"fix\"}\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nAppends wires to the wiring section.\n\n**Rewire Result:**\n```json\n{\n  \"op\": \"rewire_result\",\n  \"from\": \"test\",\n  \"result\": \"success\",\n  \"old_to\": \"done\",\n  \"new_to\": \"security-scan\"\n}\n```\n\nChanges the target of an existing wire. Used by the orchestrator when inserting\na new step into the graph: it finds a wire pointing to `done`, rewires it to\nthe new step, then wires the new step's results to terminals. This splices the\nnew step into the existing flow rather than creating a disconnected node.\n\n**Update Collect:**\n```json\n{\n  \"op\": \"update_collect\",\n  \"collect_target\": \"done\",\n  \"add_conditions\": [\n    {\"step\": \"security-scan\", \"result\": \"success\"}\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nFinds the matching `collect` clause and adds the new condition.\n\n**Validation gate:** After any mutation, the mutator calls\n`domain.Workflow.Validate()` on the result. If validation fails, the mutation is\nrejected, the original file is preserved, and the failure is logged.\n\n**DSL Serializer:** The mutator requires a round-trip-preserving serializer —\nparse into an AST that retains comments and whitespace, modify the AST, serialize\nback. This preserves user formatting and comments.\n\nBranches B and C often fire together — a new script step needs both the script\nfile (B) and the DSL wiring (C).\n\n### Stage 5: Audit Logger\n\nAfter all changes are applied:\n\n1. **Snapshot** — copies pre-change versions of all modified files to\n   `.cloche/evolution/snapshots/`\n2. **Restore** — restores a file from a named snapshot (used by the Curator\n   to roll back corrupted writes)\n3. **Log** — appends a JSONL entry to `.cloche/evolution/log.jsonl` and inserts\n   into the `evolution_log` SQLite table\n4. **Knowledge base update** — merges the Reflector's lessons into\n   `knowledge/<workflow>.jsonl` with ID-based deduplication and optional\n   pruning via `MaxPromptBullets`\n\n## Knowledge Base Structure\n\nThe knowledge base is a JSONL file — one JSON object per line, each\nrepresenting a `Lesson`. Lessons are keyed by `id` for deduplication: if a\nlesson with the same ID already exists, it is updated in place rather than\nappended. When `MaxPromptBullets` is configured and the total number of\nlessons exceeds that limit, the oldest entries are pruned to stay within\nbounds.\n\n```jsonl\n{\"id\":\"P001\",\"category\":\"prompt_improvement\",\"insight\":\"Always sanitize user inputs with html.EscapeString() before template rendering\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add sanitization rule to prompt\",\"evidence\":[\"run-abc\",\"run-def\"],\"confidence\":\"high\"}\n{\"id\":\"W001\",\"category\":\"new_step\",\"step_type\":\"script\",\"insight\":\"Added gosec security scan step\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add gosec step to workflow\",\"evidence\":[\"run-abc\",\"run-def\"],\"confidence\":\"high\"}\n{\"id\":\"F001\",\"category\":\"prompt_improvement\",\"insight\":\"Test timeout failures correlate with database connection setup\",\"suggested_action\":\"Add retry guidance to prompt\",\"evidence\":[\"run-ghi\",\"run-jkl\"],\"confidence\":\"medium\"}\n```\n\nThe structured JSONL format enables reliable deduplication by lesson ID and\nprogrammatic querying. Lessons that are superseded by newer insights with the\nsame ID are replaced automatically.\n\n## Trigger Logic\n\n### When Evolution Runs\n\nThe pipeline triggers in the daemon after every workflow run completes (success\nor failure). Smart throttling prevents waste:\n\n- **Debounce:** If runs complete in rapid succession (parallel runs on the same\n  project), wait a configurable period (default 30s) after the last completion\n  before triggering. This batches multiple runs into one analysis pass.\n- **Mutex:** If an evolution pass is already in progress for this\n  project+workflow, skip. The next run completion will pick up the slack.\n- **No-op detection:** If the Reflector finds nothing actionable (clean feature\n  runs, no patterns), the pipeline logs \"no changes\" and exits without firing\n  the executor branches.\n\n### History Window\n\nThe Collector gathers all runs since the last evolution pass (tracked via\n`evolution_log.trigger_run_id`). The knowledge base provides the long-term\nmemory — once raw runs are analyzed, their lessons persist in the knowledge base\neven as the raw data ages out. This gives the system both recency (raw run data)\nand continuity (accumulated knowledge).\n\n## Protocol Changes\n\n### gRPC (CLI to Daemon)\n\n```protobuf\nmessage RunRequest {\n  string workflow = 1;\n  string prompt = 2;\n  string project_dir = 3;   // NEW\n}\n```\n\n### Status Protocol (Agent to Daemon)\n\n```protobuf\nmessage StepStarted {\n  string step_name = 1;\n  string prompt_text = 2;    // NEW: assembled prompt\n}\n\nmessage StepCompleted {\n  string step_name = 1;\n  string result = 2;\n  string agent_output = 3;   // NEW: LLM response\n  int32 attempt_number = 4;  // NEW\n}\n```\n\n### Prompt Adapter Changes\n\nThe prompt adapter captures the assembled prompt text before invoking the agent\nand the agent's stdout after it returns. Both are forwarded to the daemon via\nthe status protocol. No changes to prompt assembly logic — the evolution system\nmodifies prompt files on disk, and the existing `file()` mechanism picks up\nchanges on the next run.\n\n## Configuration\n\nPer-project in `.cloche/config`:\n\n```toml\n[evolution]\nenabled = true                # master switch\ndebounce_seconds = 30         # wait after last run before analyzing\nmin_confidence = \"medium\"     # minimum lesson confidence to act on\nmax_prompt_bullets = 50       # cap on knowledge bullets per prompt\n```\n\nEvolution is enabled by default. Users can disable it per-project for static\nworkflows.\n\n## GEPA: Fitness Evaluation and Pareto Front\n\nThe Guided Evolutionary Prompt Adaptation (GEPA) subsystem extends the evolution\npipeline with multi-objective fitness evaluation for population-based prompt\nevolution. It lives in `internal/evolution/fitness.go`.\n\n### Fitness Records\n\nEach completed run is evaluated into a `FitnessRecord` containing:\n- **RunID / WorkflowName / Candidate** — identifies the run and its candidate\n  (e.g. a prompt version)\n- **Success** — whether the run reached `succeeded` state\n- **RetryCount** — number of step re-executions (detected by counting duplicate\n  step names in execution history)\n- **Duration** — wall-clock time from start to completion\n\nRecords are persisted as JSONL at `.cloche/evolution/fitness/<workflow>.jsonl`.\n\n### Aggregation\n\n`AggregateFitness` groups records by candidate and computes two objectives:\n\n1. **Success rate** — fraction of runs that succeeded\n2. **Efficiency** — `1 / (1 + avgRetries + avgDurationMinutes)`, rewarding\n   faster candidates with fewer retries\n\n### Pareto Front\n\n`ComputeParetoFront` returns the non-dominated set using standard Pareto\ndominance: candidate A dominates B when A is at least as good in all objectives\nand strictly better in at least one. The front represents the optimal tradeoff\nbetween reliability and speed — no candidate on the front can be improved in one\nobjective without sacrificing the other.\n\n### Population Configuration\n\nPopulation-based evolution is controlled by `PopulationConfig`:\n\n```go\ntype PopulationConfig struct {\n    Enabled          bool\n    MaxCandidates    int\n    MinRunsToPromote int\n}\n```\n\n## Future Work (Out of Scope)\n\n- **Step removal/mutation** — modifying or removing existing step definitions\n  (higher risk, needs careful design around backwards compatibility)\n- **`cloche evolve --revert <evo-id>`** — automated revert from snapshots\n- **Helpfulness tracking** — automatically detecting whether applied lessons\n  actually reduced failure rates, and pruning unhelpful ones\n- **Cross-project learning** — sharing knowledge base insights across projects\n","numLines":512,"startLine":1,"totalLines":512}}}
